The reason this compiles

    interface Furniture {}
    
    class Test {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           Furniture f; 
           Cat cat = new Cat();
           f = (Furniture)cat; //runtime error
       }
    }

is that you may very well have

    public class CatFurniture extends Cat implements Furniture {}

If you create a `CatFurniture` instance, you can assign it to `Cat cat` and that instance can be casted to `Furniture`. In other words, it&#39;s possible that some `Cat` subtype does implement the `Furniture` interface.

In your first example

    class Test {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Chair chair = new Chair();
            Cat cat = new Cat();
            chair = (Chair)cat; //compile error
        }
    }

it&#39;s impossible that some `Cat` subtype extends `Chair` unless `Cat` itself extends from `Chair`.

